{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656139"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18713"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18713"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77041"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62547"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10591"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26508"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77041"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMilk production is suppressed during pregnancy despite high circulating prolactin concentrations. The onset of lactation coincides with specific endocrine changes that occur after delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of progesterone on lactation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enhances mammary duct growth","Causes milk release","Prevents prolactin receptor activation","Increases milk protein production","Sustains milk secretion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EProgesterone\u0027s key role is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevents prolactin receptor activation\u003C/strong\u003E at mammary epithelial cells. While prolactin levels increase during pregnancy, the high progesterone concentration prevents lactation from beginning. At delivery, progesterone levels decrease rapidly, removing this inhibition and allowing milk synthesis to commence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances mammary duct growth\u003C/strong\u003E - Ductal development is primarily regulated by oestrogen\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauses milk release\u003C/strong\u003E - Milk ejection is controlled by oxytocin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases milk protein production\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of prolactin signalling\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESustains milk secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Continued milk production requires regular infant feeding and is mediated by prolactin and oxytocin\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe transition to milk production after delivery (lactogenesis stage II) occurs when progesterone withdrawal permits prolactin to exert its effects on the mammary tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Progesterone prevents milk synthesis during pregnancy by interfering with prolactin signalling at mammary cells.","Postpartum progesterone decline enables prolactin-mediated lactation to begin.","Sustained lactation depends on regular feeding and prolactin/oxytocin, independent of progesterone."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62547"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"qu